<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-180-242  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 180 242.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>DG Review  April 1989 v9 n10 p8(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The four-step: solving application performance problems can bedone in a four-step process. Here's how. (AOS-VS file)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Wilkes, Andy.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A computer system's software environment consists of the operatingand application environments.andP;  These two environments areintertwined and therefore improvements to one will probablyimprove the performance of the other.andP;  Several techniques areavailable for analysis and fine-tuning of the environments.andO;Discussed are several that are most suitable for the applicationenvironment, as well as steps necessary to analyze systemwideresource utilization.andP;  The AOS-VS and AOS-VS II operating systemand application environment are used as examples, although thetechniques are suitable for any other environment.andP;  The four stepsconsists of observing the performance of the entire computersystem when the application is running a typical environment,evaluating the application systems running on the system,optimizing components of the environment to improve performance,and monitoring the analysts efforts and making final adjustments.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     TutorialSoftware ModificationOperating EnvironmentsProblem SolvingPerformance ImprovementSystems AnalysisOperating SystemsApplications.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>